			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: finaly have fade now what?<a name="70941"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Dec 13 04 2:07 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Once you get used to having FM, you'll use it all the time. It really is a defining feature of a high level bard. It will change the way you play your game. And it changes what group members expect of you.
<br />
I've never used a fade message... and I've actually never had a problem with that. If you're pulling, people can see the mob(s) behind you. If suddenly you go invis and the mob(s) stop dead in their tracks, pretty much everyone with a 2-digit IQ can figure out whats going on.
<br />

<br />
Its an awesome utility, but you'll find that you'll now be scrambling for FT (mana regen) items since the cost for FM is so high. Maybe you'll decide to choose the FT aa's to work on next... I doubt you'd regret it. Personally, the very first AA's I got after FM were all defensive. It makes a big difference if you pull a lot, and if you have to tank a hard hitting mob every now and then.
<br />
As Pizzicato mentioned, Boastful Bellow is a nice AA too. Its instant. It has a longer casting range than pretty much any song we've got (even with with your distance AA's maxed) and you can also use it to break mezzes, which can come in handy if you have to get crafty on a pull (it won't break a mez if it gets resisted). I use it a lot when I'm farming for tradeskill or quest items, cause I'm lazy and don't want to have to chase everything down all the time. BB and FM are the only 2 AA abilities that I have hotkeyed on every one of my hotkey pads. Bellow is very handy for pulling... use bellow to get aggro, and then slow the mob on the run back to group so your chanter/shammy doesn't take as much of a beating if their slow gets resisted. It also interrupts NPC spells because of the stun effect... not so much on higher level mobs (like EPs or beyond) but its great to use as a stun on upper-mid level mobs. In PvP it will also knock a PC off their horse and interrupt their casts. The level limit for the stun does not apply in PvP... you can stun level 70 people with BB as long as they don't resist it. Its only an instant stun - it does not stun them for any period of time, but it interrupts auto-run, knocks people off mounts, interrupts casts, and breaks invis/FD. Not sure what the resist check on PC's is, but its kind of high I believe.
<br />
Also, when you feel comfortable with it, get run5. Mobs in Riftseekers (a zone available only to lvl 69+ folks) run at run5, and you can't cast selos there. Run5 is faster than our indoor selos.. faster than shrew.. faster than SoW... faster than all giant's speed. Its a buttload of AA's and probably not worth getting right away, but I'm glad to have it. Many people shunned it for a while, but once I got it I loved it because as a bard I'm expected to pull... indoors or out... whether I have mana for FM or not. Also, I've heard SoE is going to do an AA refund for those who have run5... and the cost for it is going down. Those who have run5 are supposed to recieve 5 AA back for the run5 ability. Not sure about run4.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
